April is Child Abuse Prevention Month, and across the country, states are reporting fewer calls to child abuse hotlines, not because officials believe there are fewer cases but because they're going unreported.
Arizona's calls are down a third compared with previous weeks, and Nevada has seen a 14% drop compared with March 2019.
“Everyone, whether you’re a store clerk, a mailman, a neighbor or a relative, everyone has the responsibility of reporting child abuse,” said New Hampshire Gov.
Chris Sununu, whose state has seen calls drop by half in recent weeks.
The organization is encouraging school counselors to make sure school websites list community and national crisis hotlines.